thread.title: $A higher ahead of RBA decision

title: $A higher ahead of RBA decision
text:
Mon, Oct 5, 2015, 6:42 PM AEDT - Australia Markets closed $A higher ahead of RBA decision AAP – 1 hour 9 minutes ago Recommend Print 
The Australian dollar is higher but expectations the Reserve Bank will give a negative outlook on the local economy has tamed its gains. 
At 1700 AEDT on Monday, the local unit was trading at 70.68 US cents, up from 70.46 cents on Friday. 
It hit an intraday high of 70.80 US cents around 1300 AEDT before losing some ground. 
A weaker greenback following disappointing US employment figures on Friday gave the Aussie a boost at the weekend. 
Positive reaction from the local and Asian share markets on Monday then pushed it higher, IG market analyst Angus Nicholson said. 
However, he said the Aussie was unable to hit 71 US cents as investors turned their attention to the upcoming Reserve Bank cash rate decision. 
While the RBA is expected to keep the benchmark interest rate on hold, he said there was concern about the central bank's outlook on the Australian economy. 
"There has been a range of weakening local data, particularly from the property sector of late," he said. 
"If there is any mention of that in the RBA's statement and if they express concern about the local economy there could be a sharp selloff in the Aussie and this is what is weighing on the unit this afternoon." 
US non-farm payroll figures on Friday showed that 142,000 jobs were added to the world's largest economy in September, well below expectations of a gain of 205,000, while the unemployment rate was unchanged at 5.1 per cent. 
At 1700 AEDT, one Australian dollar was buying 84.83 Japanese yen, up from 84.56 on Friday, and 62.95 euro cents, down from 63.06 euro cents. 
Meanwhile, the Australian bond market is firmer as more investors price in chances of a future interest rate cut. 
At 1630 AEDT on Monday, the December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.415 (implying a yield of 2.585 per cent), up from 97.345 (2.655 per cent) on Friday.
